@node introduction "StUC v1.09 (Introduction)"
StUC is a utility I wrote because no other program did what this one does in
the way I liked.

All  StUC  is,  is  a  little  program that reads all the commodities in the
drawer where all the commodities are kept and lets you select which ones you
want  to  load  via  a  very  user  friendly interface.  The commodities are
presented  in a window and you can click on them and turn them on and off at
will.   If  you need as much available memory, you can also exit the program
without loading any.

The  program  also  makes  use of tool types which means you can pretty much
configure the program how you like.

Versions  up  to and including 1.05 were written in assembler by myself, but
because I wanted to give StUC a GUI I rewrote it in E.

If  you  think  that the file size of StUC is too large, send me a disk with
return postage and I'll send you the assembler version including full source
code.   Please  don't  send  empty  disks - I'll accept anything LEGAL but I
would  much  prefer  some  E source code no matter how basic!  The assembler
version is only around 2500 bytes but has no GUI!
@endnode
@node exampledir "StUC v1.09 (Example Dir)"
Just  in  case  there  are  a few of you who can't quite understand what I'm
blabbering  on  about  with the installation procedure, here is my directory
listing showing where the files are...

	L (dir)
	  WBStart-Handler
	Libs (dir)
	  Icon.library		   GadTools.library
	  ReqTools.library
	WbStartup (dir)
	  StUC			   StUC.info
	StartUp (dir)
	  DiaryReq			DiaryReq.info
	  MouseBlanker			MouseBlanker.info
	  SwazInfo			SwazInfo.info
	  ToolsDaemon			ToolsDaemon.info
	  CapsShift			CapsShift.info

And for my tool types...
	DONOTWAIT
	USETTYPES=YES
	LOAD=SELECTED
	DEFAULT=ENABLED
	NEWFONT=YES
	PATH=SYS:StartUp/
	CENTREX=YES
	CENTREY=YES
@endnode
@node requirements "StUC v1.09 (Requirements)"
Handlers:
	wbstart-handler v1.4

Libraries:
	icon.library v33
	gadtools.library v37
	reqtools.library v37

Kickstart v37 or better (KS2)
@endnode
@node usage "StUC v1.09 (Usage)"
StUC will only run from Workbench.  If you try running it from AmigaDOS then
you'll  get a small message and the program will exit which is really taking
the piss out of PC programs!  :)

		+-----------------------------------------+
		|StUC v1.09				  |
		+-----------------------------------------+
		| +------------------------+   StartUp    |
		| |			   |  Controller  |
		| |			   |		  |
		| |			   | @{"@| Disabled" link disabled} |
		| |   @{"Commodities List" link cxlist}    | @{"@| Selected" link selected} |
		| |			   | @{" On  " link on}@{" Off " link off} |
		| |			   | @{"Information" link information} |
		| |			   | @{"   Start   " link start} |
		| +------------------------+		  |
		| @{"            Status Window             " link statuswin} |
		+-----------------------------------------+
@endnode
@node disabled "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Disabled)"
Hotkey: 1

The text inside the gadget cycles between: @{b}Enabled@{ub}
					   @{b}Disabled@{ub}

@{b}Enabled@{ub}
	Allows the selected commodity to be loaded.

@{b}Disabled@{ub}
	The selected commodity will not be loaded.
@endnode
@node selected "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Selected)"
Hotkey: 2

The text inside the gadget cycles between: @{b}All@{ub}
					   @{b}None@{ub}
					   @{b}Selected@{ub}

@{b}All@{ub}
	The  gadgets  @{"On" link on}  and  @{"Off" link off}  and  enabled and it it now possible to
	enable  or  disable all of the commodities at once instead of having
	to select them all individually.

@{b}None@{ub}
	Select  this  followed by @{"Start" link start} to quit StUC without loading any of
	the commodities.

@{b}Selected@{ub}
	This allows you to enable and disable each commodity separately.
@endnode
@node on "StUC v1.09 (Usage: On)"
Hotkey: nN

When  this  gadget  is  enabled, it will enable all of the commodities.  You
could then use @{"Selected" link selected} to disable one or two selected commodities.
@endnode
@node off "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Off)"
Hotkey: fF

When  this  gadget  is enabled, it will disable all of the commodities.  You
could then use @{"Selected" link selected} to enable one or two selected commodities.
@endnode
@node information "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Information)"
Hotkey: iI

This  gadget  allows  you  to view the program credits and other information
like my address, some greets to friends, as well as some brief help.
@endnode
@node start "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Start)"
Hotkey: sS

Clicking on this gadget starts StUC loading the commodities.  Any which have
been disabled will not be loaded.

If  a  commodity  hasn't  got a ".info" file then you'll be presented with a
requester  telling you the name of the commodity and that is doesn't have an
accompanying icon file.  You'll be asked you if you want StUC to create one.
You can click on "Yes" to create one or "No" to leave it alone.

If  you  click  on "No" then every time you boot up you'll keep getting told
about there not being an icon so it would probably be best to click on "Yes"
instead.   The  image  that is saved is that of the icon that comes with the
commodities  for Workbench 3.  Maybe in a future version I'll let you select
your own icon images!

Please  notice  that  when  StUC  creates  an icon for a commodity, that the
commodity  is  NOT loaded.  Reset and boot up again to load it.  The default
tool types included with the new icon are "DONOTWAIT" and "CX_PRIORITY=0".
@endnode
@node cxlist "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Commodities List)"
Hotkey: - (Select the previous commodity)
	+ (Select the next commodity)

This is where the list of commodities appear that have been read in from the
drawer  where you keep them.  The commodity you've clicked on will appear in
the @{"status window" link statuswin}.
@endnode
@node statuswin "StUC v1.09 (Usage: Status Window)"
When  you  click  on @{"Start" link start} and start loading the commodities, the commodity
currently being loaded will be shown here.
@endnode
@node installation "StUC v1.09 (Installation)"
I originally wrote an installation script but deleted it because it deleted
a friend's commodities!  Here is what you must do to install STuC...

1. Create a new drawer in SYS: called "Startup"
2. Move all existing files from "WBStartup" to "Startup"
3. Place StUC in the "WBStartup" drawer
4. Make sure you've got the libraries "gadtools.library", "reqtools.library"
   and "icon.library".
5. Copy the handler "WbStart-handler" to L: if you've not already got it.

Once these five simple steps have been done, just sit back, reset and watch!

Note  that  by  using  the  tool  type  @{"PATH" link tooltypes},  you  can  actually  move your
commodities  to  a  different  location.   So if you're low on disk space on
DH0:, you can move them to another partition!
@endnode
@node tooltypes "StUC v1.09 (Tool Types)"
By  using  tool  types,  it  is possible to influence how StUC starts up and
looks like.  The available tool types are:

@{b}USETTYPES@{ub} (YES/NO)
	This  tells  StUC  whether  you want to ignore the tool types or use
	them.  Anything other than "YES" tells StUC to ignore them.
	Default=NO

@{b}WINTOP@{ub} (Integer value greater than 0)
	This  tells  StUC  how far down the screen you want it to open.  The
	default value is used for invalid settings.
	Default=65

@{b}WINLEFT@{ub} (Integer value greater than 0)
	This  tells StUC how far out from the left of the screen you want it
	to  open  it's  window.   The  default  value  is  used  for invalid
	settings.
	Default=151

@{b}LOAD@{ub} (ALL/NONE/SELECTED)
	This  tells  StUC  which  you  want  displayed  when StUC opens it's
	window.  See @{"Selected" link selected} for more information.
	Default=ALL

@{b}DEFAULT@{ub} (ENABLED/DISABLED)
	This  tells  StUC  in  what  state  you  want  the commodities to be
	automatically set.
	Default=ENABLED

@{b}NEWFONT@{ub} (YES/NO)
	Do  you  want  the  standard  topaz  font (NO) or the new font (YES)
	you've chosen from the font preferences?
	Default=NO

@{b}PATH@{ub} (String)
	This is the drawer where your commodities have been placed.
	Default=SYS:StartUp/

@{b}CENTREX@{ub} (YES/NO)
	Centre the window horizontally.  This overrides WINLEFT.
	Default=NO

@{b}CENTREY@{ub} (YES/NO)
	Centre the window vertically.  This overrides WINTOP.
	Default=NO
@endnode
@node bugs "StUC v1.09 (Bugs)"
As  far  as  I  know  there  aren't any more b*gs left.  I've done extensive
testing of StUC and I'm no longer having problems with it (I decided to test
it  for a few months before releasing it into the public domain!) Should you
discover a bug which has managed to evade capture then I would appreciate it
a great deal if you could let me know so I can try and fix it.

When  sending  me  a  bug report, it would make it a lot easier if you could
give  me  as  much  information about your machine like memory and any extra
devices  connected,  what  files  you were trying to load, did they all have
icon  files,  and  if  StUC  give  you a software failure, what is the error
number?  This would make removal of the error so much easier...
@endnode
@node history "StUC v1.09 (History)"
@{b}v1.00@{ub} »»» @{i}Beta test version @{ui}
	  This version wasn't able to load the commodities at this time, but
	  was only able to open the windows and detect the mouse buttons.

@{b}v1.02@{ub} »»» @{i}First public release @{ui}
	  Made  it  able to load the commodities, implemented the SHIFT keys
	  for when the program loads and rewrote the about text.

@{b}v1.03@{ub} »»» @{i}Next enhanced release@{ui}
	  No  bugs  removed, just made it run smoother.  If left to wait for
	  either  of  the mouse buttons then it doesn't flash the window off
	  then on again.  I've also added a RMBTrap so the title bar doesn't
	  flash when the right mouse button is pressed.

@{b}v1.04@{ub} »»» @{i}Updated documentation & single group release@{ui}
	  It  seems  that StUC doesn't like some Amigas from two bug reports
	  I've  received  lately  via  a  fellow  Carnage  member, Kei.  The
	  problem seems to lie on Amigas that have been accelerated and have
	  some  strange  add-ons.   It  is unclear at this moment what it is
	  exactly  that is causing the problem, but I've just tested it with
	  almost  every  commodity I have and they all work fine.  I've also
	  made  this  a  100%  Carnage  release  as  making it a Carnage and
	  Cybertek release somehow confused some people!?

@{b}v1.05@{ub} »»» @{i}Removal of the external command BRUN@{ui}
	  I've  modified  the code ever so slightly resulting  in an extra 4
	  byte  increase in the main executable.  This alteration results in
	  the third external command BRUN (RunBack) from not being required.

@{b}v1.06@{ub} »»» @{i}Converted to E!@{ui}
	* Totally re-written in Amiga E
	* New GUI added

@{b}v1.07@{ub} »»» @{i}Rewritten due to major problem@{ui}
	* Total rewrite
	  Because  of the way I loaded the commodities in previous versions,
	  none of the tooltypes in each of the commodities were used.
	* Commodities can be selectively loaded rather than none or all
	  Big welcome to the list view window
	* Tooltypes have been added
	  It is now possible to configure StUC for every time you boot up
	* Unfortunate increase in file size (not much, though!)
	* I've left Carnage and joined Area 51 so the group name has changed

@{b}v1.08@{ub} »»» @{i}Minor alterations@{ui}
	* An itsy bitsy bug fix
	* Code optimised

@{b}v1.08@{ub} »»» @{i}Massive improvements@{ui}
	* Keyboard shortcuts added (at the request of Xes!)
	* Most of the code re-written and optimised
	* ListView window itself now shows what commodity is selected
	* Two new tooltypes added, CENTREX and CENTREY to centre correctly
	  on any screen
	* The help text inside the program has been partially re-written
	* Icon saved out when a commodity without an icon is found has been
	  altered slightly
@endnode
@node contactaddy "StUC v1.09 (Contact Address)"
If  you  have any ideas for improvements, want to report a bug, want to send
me a postcard or just want to trade, then I can be contacted at:

@{i}Snail: @{ui} Ivan Oliver
	39 Beckly Court
	Armada Way
	PLYMOUTH
	PL1 1LD
	England
Please mark the envelope with "Re: StUC109" in the top left.

If  sending me a bug report, please don't forget to mention little important
details like...
	o The model of Amiga you're using (eg. A600, A1200)
	o The amount of memory you have in chip, fast and public.
	o If your Amiga is accelerated, and if so, to what speed?
	o If you get a guru meditation, what is the eight digit hex number?
	o Any Commodore or third party add-ons (eg. CD-ROM)
	o If  you  own a hard drive, and if so, what size and what size each
	  individual partition is, especially SYS:
@endnode
